name: Car Alarm Horn, Walking Past, A.wav
description: Raw audio of walking past a car with its alarm/horn going off. The car had malfunctioned and the owner was desperately trying to turn it off - might as well make the most of it and record it! The recording starts about 10m away from the car, approaching as close as 1m before moving away again, at which point the recorder was pointed forwards as opposed to the car. The owner did eventually shut it off about 10s after the recording ends, so you can sleep well tonight. This sound is not in the public domain. Please attribute/credit the sound if you use it. If you would prefer to not have to give attribution, then take a look at the attribution-free license. An example of how you might credit is by putting this in the description/credits: "Car Alarm, Walking Past, A.wav" by InspectorJ (www.jshaw.co.uk) of Freesound.org If any of these sounds have been of help, and you are feeling charitable, please do consider donating to Freesound to help keep the site running (a link is also on the home page). Any donations are greatly appreciated! And for more awesome sounds, do please check out my sound libraries or SFX store. Please comment on where you intend to use the sound, and feel free to post a link to the work where you used it if you want (I enjoy watching/listening to anything you create!) The sound was recorded using a "H1 Zoom recorder" on 22nd September 2017. Note: Audio quality is always better when downloaded.

name: Car horn short.wav
description: I recently contributed a track to a Triple LP set of krautrock cover versions ("Head Music 2", released by Fruits De Mer Records, December 2020). The song I chose to cover was Kraftwerk's "Autobahn". If you know the track, you'll know that it uses synthesised traffic sounds alongside recordings of the same. On my version, I achieved these in three ways: 1) I downloaded some public domain traffic sound effects from elsewhere here on freesound.org (thanks, guys!) 2) I got in my car with my Zoom recorder and made my own recordings of the engine starting, stopping, etc 3) I made my own sound effects using virtual synths and effects in Ableton Live 10 This particular sound falls into the second category. Let me stress that while the song "Autobahn" is copyrighted, these are isolated sound effects and are not covered by copyright. I'm making them available here under a public domain licence. If you download and use any of these samples, please let me know in the comments what you did with them. It's not compulsory but it would be interesting to know what people did with these sounds.

name: REUTER_Jennyfer_2018_2019_Car_Accident.wav
description:
I recorded the sound on the street, then a sound of a car that starts and rolls. I generated a white noise at 0.8 amplitude, I added a distortion effect, then I used a progressive pitch variation, a hard limit and the Tromolo effect. Then, I recorded a noise of a plastic water bottle crushed. I generated a sinusoidal wave at 440 Hz. I used the effect “Wahwah” to create a sound like that of a beating heart. And I added a silence to suppose the victim’s death. I normalized to avoid saturation. This sound tells the story of a driver who takes his car, starts it, rolls, accelerates, another user honks to warn of danger and the driver collides with a pedestrian.

name: De carro pela cidade [stereo] By car through the city
description:
Sons do caminho. Entrando e dirigindo carro pela cidade em tarde vazia até chegar ao destino. Chave, portas, ignição. Motor, ar-condicionado. Paisagem. Sinal de alerta, buzina. Ligar o carro. Puxar freio de mão. Sair do carro.

Gravado na rodovia entre Belém e Castanhal, Santa Izabel, Pará, Amazônia, Brasil. Gravação parte do projeto Banco Sonoro Amazônico. Em estéreo com Zoom H6.

// projeto Banco Sonoro Amazônico

Ao utilizar o arquivo, fazer referência ao Banco Sonoro Amazônico.
Autor: José Viana
Ano: 2022
Agradecimentos: Cassio Tavernard

--

Way sounds. Entering and driving car through the city in empty afternoon until reaching the destination. Key, doors, ignition. Engine, air conditioning. Landscape. Warning sign, horn. Turn on the car. Pull handbrake. Get out of the car.

Recorded on the highway between Belém and Castanhal, Santa Izabel, Pará, Amazon, Brazil. Recording part of the Banco Sonoro Amazônico project. In stereo with Zoom H6.

// Amazon Sound Bank project

When using the file, make reference to Banco Sonoro Amazônico.

name: Train Horn
description:
This is a horn of a train moving by. 

There was also a sound of caution, like a small telephone, to let everyone know a train is approaching, a noise again (there's always this noise, I'm sick of it), very quiet car engines and a heavy sound hitting the rail of the train itself - these are all the sounds I "erased" with denoising function to get a clearer main sound - of the horn of the train. Of course I couldn't make it crystal clean.

It was recorded in the March of 2014. Quite far from the city, it was still a bit cold, and dry, but the spring had been approaching already, on this sunny morning.

name: Raining Car Soundscape
description: This soundscape idea was recommended to me by Night Chemistry, and allowed for me to experiment with more realistic sounds as well as how they should be altered to be perceived from within a car. Spot Fx such as thunder and lighting were relevant inclusions to amplify that low rainy mood. A radio background was implemented to give the soundscape variety in what one would normally hear from the car, and a passing horn spot Fx was another in similar vain (with automated panning to give the perception that a car has went past with the horn - basic surround sound).

name: LS_34039_FR_TourDeFrance.wav
description:
Tour de France. 
The ‘’Tour de France’’ is a famous professional cycling race held in France every year in July. During 3 weeks, the competitors race all around the country while thousands of people come on the side of the roads to encourage them. 
Here, we’re on the side of the road during the last day of this race. 
First, you can hear an helicopter in the background, cars and motorcycles passing by on the road, safety warning, and some horn. Then, the racers arrive, and you can hear the spectators’ encouragement, applauses, and the bicycles passing by quickly. 
Recorded in July 2018 with an Olympus LS-3 (internal microphones, TRESMIC system on). 
Fade in/out and high pass filter at 160Hz -6dB/oct applied in audacity.

name: 140619_Bike_06_R.wav
description:
4ch surround recording of a bike riding through city traffic (Leipzig/Germany) on an evening in late spring.
Recorded with a Zoom H2 with a Rycote windshield in a shock mount fastened to the center frame above the pedals.
All recordings in the set are raw from the recorder and will usually need a hi-pass filter to deal with the rumble.

Waiting at a red traffic light equipped with a ticker to assist blind pedestrians, while a tram passes on the intersecting street. Then the light turns green, gear shifting and starting to pedal, turning into the intersecting major street with 4 lanes and a tram line while a car honks it's horn. Steady pedaling and freewheeling as numerous cars pass, finally stopping and dismounting.

These are the REAR channels, mics set to 120° dispersion.

name: Car vs. Freight Train.wav
description: The train is going by just as the impatient teenager comes around the bend. He puts on his breaks, honks his horn, and yells "Hey!" as if threatening to try to do something drastic. The train gives a warning whistle in reply, but the teenager pays no heed. He sees a small rise in the road, so he assumes that, if he drives with enough speed, he might fly over the train and onto the other side. So he accelerates towards the train, but the rise fails to give him enough hight, and he crashes into the train. We fade to black. Sounds used: http://www.freesound.org/people/RHumphries/sounds/1934/ http://www.freesound.org/people/boteman/sounds/57196/ http://www.freesound.org/people/han1/sounds/19026/ http://www.freesound.org/people/sazman/sounds/7876/ http://www.freesound.org/people/CGEffex/sounds/99960/ http://www.freesound.org/people/Syna-Max/sounds/35902/

name: 240905_090904_FR_Calm_modern_apartment_rainy_day
description:
Calm modern apartment atmosphere during a rainy day (binaural, please use headset for 3D effects). 
I made this recording in the living room of my 1st floor apartment, located in a suburb of Paris (France) during a rainy day. 
The double glazing windows were closed, and one can hear the calm indoor atmosphere of the building, with some noise and cars passing by in the wet street outside, while rain is falling down on the guardrail of the balcony. At #3:39, one can hear a car honking, and at about 6:40, one can hear the rumble of the garbage truck approaching. It arrives near the building about one minute later. 
Recorded in September 2024 with a zoom h6essential and Immersive Soundscapes EarSight Binaural microphones. 
Fade in/out and high pass filter at 60Hz -6dB/oct applied in Audacity. 
(If you want to use this sound as a mono audio file, you may have to delete one channel to avoid phase issues).

name: 231005_2562_FR_Traffic_in_Paris.wav
description:
Traffic in Paris (binaural, please use headset for 3D effects). 
I made this recording during a warm autumn morning, just near a stoplight  bordering the crossing of several cobbled streets, in the surroundings of Cambronne metro station, in Paris (France). 
One can hear different vehicles (cars, motorcycles, mopeds, buses, trucks, as well as bicycles) passing by in the streets, honking at times, while some people are walking and chatting on the sidewalk. In the background, hum from the city, and sometimes, squeaking noise from the brakes of the metro stopping in the nearby outdoor subway station. Quite a typical Parisian atmosphere, in my opinion. 
Recorded in October 2023 with an Olympus LS-P4 and Ohrwurm 3D binaural microphones. 
Fade in/out and high pass filter at 60Hz -6dB/oct applied in Audacity. 
(If you want to use this sound as a mono audio file, you may have to delete one channel to avoid phase issues).

name: 120305_WashMonmnt02.wav
description:
Noon atmo on the National Mall in Washington D.C. next to the Washington Monument. The recorder is on the outer ring path around the monument, facing north towards the Ellipse and the White House. Lots of sirens from diverse fire-engines, EMS vehicles and police cars can be heard in the far range speeding down Constitution Ave. What sounds (and can well be used... ;-) ) like a scene from a catastrophe movie is, in fact, simply the safety detail for Marine One, the President's helicopter, arriving to their assigned stations near the landing field.
Recorded in March 2012 with a Zoom H2, mics set to 90° dispersion.

description: A car passed by and sounded its horn rhythmically: instantly other cars, motorcycles, people clapping hands, repeated the melody. What does it mean? We guess that nothing. name: March_LV.mp3
description: March LV from John Cage’s "A Dip in the Lake" interpreted by recording in Chicago on March 14th, 2020. The recording locations include Orchard St. and Belmont Ave. In Arlington Heights, W. Diversey Ave./N. Paulina St. and N. Wolcott Ave., the lake off Glencoe, and the lake “further out.” The recording guides the listener through the city through the simplicity of birds, a mix of car ride tunes and news in an Uber, and marching to privacy at the lake. Three noteworthy sounds from the recording include the ringing of a bell and the honking of a horn on a child’s bicycle (2’09”), a news report on the state of COVID-19 at the time (2’57”), and the crashing of waves (4’31”). The lake off Glencoe is a really inspiring spot to reflect, especially during the time of hardship this recording was captured during. The roughness of my footsteps with the wind blowing towards the end of the piece really hits home with the mentality of marching forward even in times of adversity.

Boys on 50cc scooters. Look at me being nice and tough, that's what they look like. A trains fast over the steel bridge of the river. A grandfather on a bicycle stops with his story and says "hello" to the microphone and the grandson sitting on the back smiles. Voices of walking and cycling people. A small speedboat crosses the river 100 meters away. Another train. That was all folks. Setting; Summer evening boulevard with embankment on 100m from river. Boulevard on 10m. Left the steel railway-bridge. Right the constant humming of the busy Highway A2. Mics in direction of the river. People on their balcony behind me. Others quietly walk and cycle past. name: WetNightEarlySpringSmallTownPeepers8MinuteVersionandTraffic41HzMarch29th2018.WAV
description:
A nice wet-themed ambiance of early spring in a small Midwestern town in the US.
The spring peepers dominate, always in the background.  The American Toads trill off and on (:38----1:04,     2:09-----2:31,     5:50----6:07,   6:25----6:40)
There is also a distant dog bark, with echo at 3:31.  Distant Car horn at 3:57 .
Since this was recorded on a busy Weeknight at 7PM, a lot of distant car doors and people picking up and dropping off kiddos for basketball practice, choir practice and other ancient extracurricular activities.  There is a particularly good door open and slam and muted conversations at 6:43 to 6:56  and again at 7:17
Stereo recording made on Thursday night March 29th, 2018 using a Sound Devices 702 and an AudioTechnica BP4025 stereo microphone.  The original was recorded at the very high sample rate of 196HZ.
Enjoy a  town winding down and internalizing on a cold, drippy wet night in either very late Winter, or very early Spring.

I recorded this binaural audio file in Calapan city (Oriental Mindoro, Philippines) in the evening of January 1st, 2019, during the fireworks held for new year. 
In this file, you can hear fireworks and firecrackers, the bells of the cathedral which are ringing for welcoming the procession following Santo-Nino (Jesus Christ), people watching and enjoying the fireworks, vehicles and horns in the street, a police car passing by, and also a Catholic song (Filipino language) broadcasted in the speakers of the cathedral.

Fade in/out applied in Audacity.

name: LS_34226_PH_Tricycle.mp3
description:
Ride a tricycle in Philippines. (binaural, please use headset for 3D effect)
I made this recording while travelling in a tricycle going from Calapan city to Baco (Oriental Mindoro,, Philippines(. 
A tricycle is a cheap transportation usually used by many Filipino people for short trips. It consists in a small motorbike with a side-car. 
Here, I’m sitting in the side-car, with the driver riding the motorcycle on my left. You can hear the engine of the tricycle, sounds coming from the surroundings (vehicles passing by, horns, people’s voices coming from the side of the road, and regularly, you can hear the driver shouting “Baco Baco” to inform people around that they can ride if they’re interested to go there too. 
Recorded in January 2019 with an Olympus LS-3 and Soundman OKM I binaural microphones (version 2018). 
Fade in/out and high pass filter at 80Hz -6dB/oct applied in Audacity.

name: file0227.wav
description:
Stereo recording using an M-Audio Microtrack with the standard T-mic.
The calliope truck has driven off to the north, and is about a block away.  Some people are talking, then the calliope makes an attempt at the Highland Reel, then shifts it to a higher key.  Car horn.  Wind noise.  I am walking briskly away from the area.  At 1:15 there is heavy traffic on the Marietta Pike.  At 1:44 I am approaching some fixed noise source on the right- a compressor or blower?  A car pulls in nearby, tire noise on stones.  Wind noise.  Throughout the track there is the calliope in the distance.  Wind blown leaves.  Birdsong.  All the while I am walking briskly down the street.  At 4:15 you hear my footsteps.  From 5:15 to 5:27 an antique car passes- unusual engine sound.  I cross over the street through some grass.  Birdsong and calliope.  At 7:15 I am in an alley. I pass a man and a woman talking.  At 8:00 I cross another street- I wait for a car to pass.  I approach some men working at a church- some are trimming a hedge, some are installing flashing.  At 9:16 a large semi passes on the street ahead.  I walk beside another heavily traveled street- Columbia Avenue.  A plane passes overhead.

name: Sea dramatics on cliffs around Zawn Wells, near Land's End (lower position)
description: Majestic chunky waves ride in and hit the cliffs broadside-on, with heavy thuds and impressive splashdowns from the plumes or walls of spray that shoot up, with beautifully discreet atmospheric foghorn (actually 'whistle') soundings coming into and out of focus. Impressive deep heavy rumbles from sea action on cliff base immediately below recorder. This is the lower of two concurrent recordings I made here on 12 March 2014, near Land's End, Penwith, Cornwall, UK. The upper one was directly overlooking Zawn Wells, a quite narrow small inlet, while this one was a little lower and 'round the corner' off to the left, just a little down the cliff slope, and rather blocked off from the sea action in Zawn Wells, and capturing instead a lot of rumbling from sea action against the cliff directly below there. I hurried like a bat out of hell from my early afternoon recording session at Zawn Rinny, by Gwennap Head, for I realized that there could be super-duper sea dramatics around Zawn Wells, and made it from the former in just an hour, with my quite heavy rucksack making that quite an achievement for me. But as I was getting near I had a heart-sink moment and disappointment, for the Longships 'foghorn' was sounding. I'd have welcomed a real foghorn — they have style! — but the bland little rather high-pitched 'whistle' really made it pointless to record. When I arrived, overlooking Zawn Wells, the sea dramatics were great, but that dratted 'foghorn' was continuing, repeating every 10 seconds. I was about to pick up my pack again and make for the Land's End car park to start my return hitch-hike to Exeter, but prudently checked that choice by means of a procedure I nowadays call Helpfulness Testing (look that up in my Glossary page), and got a strong indication that, regardless of how I was feeling about that confounded 'foghorn', it would be much better that I still spend an hour making two concurrent recordings here as though there were no such issue. However, once the recording was running, I started getting tingling up my spine, and beginning to recognise that I might be getting something really special here. It was reminding me of the musical 'device' I'd used in movement 3 of my Symphony 6, where I had a high D tone running through most of that movement, which gave the music (a symbolic battle of humans against 'the elements' on the mountain K2) a strange 'metaphysical' quality and sense of some powerful 'higher' purpose. Similarly here, that eerie distant whistle tone drifting in and out of audibility was giving the impression of intensifying the sense of drama, and suggesting some deep metaphysical aspect of it all. On editing the recordings afterwards I found that impression was reinforced. I did have one regret, though. I noticed how both recordings had failed to reproduce clearly the movement of the waves from left to right; there was only a vague impression of that happening. — It wasn't till 2016, when I started using the PCM-D100 recorder, that I realized how atrocious the M10's stereo imaging really was. How I then wished for being able to repeat that spectacular with the D100 and hear the exact position of each wave as it moves across the soundstage! I did enhance the stereo image of both recordings with software, but they're still nothing like they'd be if they'd been recorded with the D100. Unfortunately, it would be a quite rare occurrence that a sufficiently large swell would accompany very light local wind and offshore sea fog, so the chances of my being able to get a repeat performance, especially with the fog 'horn', would be virtually nil. Advisory For a reasonable approximation to the loudness of the original soundscape, a playing volume of 3dB above a normal sensible volume level is needed. High-grade headphones are particularly recommended in order to hear all the detail. Also, because the stereo imaging has been enhanced, that may cause a certain phasiness or phase cancellation points when you listen through certain speakers, whereas that effect doesn't occur when listening through headphones. From the upper recorder position, overlooking Zawn Wells (inlet on right), during this recording. From same position, getting the view out to the Land's End complex. Techie stuff: The recorder was a Sony PCM-M10, with just one furry windshield — a Røde DeadKitten (original, more effective, version) —, and placed on a Zipshot Mini tripod (more midi than mini). Post-recording processing was to apply EQ in Audacity to correct for the muffling effect of the windshield, and more recent processing with the A1 Stereo Control VST plugin (160% widening). Please remember to give this recording a rating — Thank you!

name: Thunder in the City 11 pm 130727_03.ogg
description: Most horizontal, high altitude, calm thunderstorm coming and going in calm suburban residence during late evening/Night. Sometimes a car passing, a dog baking and sometime a human voice. Most of the time just the rain in he gutter on plants, trees, on the street and on he cars and the far and sometimes close thunder. There is a great variation in rain, wind and thunder sound-level. My metaphor on this recording is getting older, disability, death represented by thunder, wind and rain and the daily life that continues far away in the background represented by the other sounds in the background. Life is meaningless , so enjoy it! Useful as background in film, movie, game and radio-play etc. Pick out your part! Or.... Fall asleep on this recording? Swami klankbeeld ;-) Haha Remarks: 00.20 dog barking 02.16 dog barking 02.35 man shouting something shortly 03.10 dog barking 03.27 bike 06.45 car 07.37 car 08.50 car coming and shut down smashing doors 09.55 car 13.05 closing garage door 14.26 car horn 17.07 closing aluminium indoor shutters 35.15-78.30 high altitude thunder and strong winds and heavy rains, all coming in large waves 51.20 car 55.14 car horn 78.30-end; last rain and thunder and gutter-noise to the end of recording. WARNING! Play on low level, because the levels variate between -48 and 0 dB. Recorded; starting July 27th 2013 11 pm, out of second floor window in calm suburban environment in the Netherlands. Using two Primo EM172 omni microphones in AB45 setting in a DIY blimp > Sony PCM D50. Sound-correction for blimps with Audacity (from1-16kHz from 0 to +9dB log, >16kHz +9dB). This is a modern high quality -q10 (1500kbps) OGG Vobis compression file (48000Hz/16bit). The quality is almost as good as the 48/24-WAV original file. You can easily use this file in HD-film and HIFI music-tracks. The sound-quality is, after this compression technique still very high The file size reduction is about 75% of the 2304kbps WAV-track When you use this sound it would be nice if you spent a voluntarily donation to freesound. name: city evening hum winter LONG 130220_02.flac
description: Standing between two 5 story buildings. It's a cold and calm winter evening between 7-8 pm. Audible: The last people come home, one with a trolley, from there work. In the front several apartment buildings. The humming of the air-conditioners on that buildings in the quiet parts of this recording. Sometimes someone walks by, some on high heels or hard soles. The far talking of people at the entrance of the apartments. Far church-bells and carillon down-town. The railway station is just around the corner. I hear the whistle of the ticket inspector ones. The nice sound of the junctions of the railway. The best way of listen is by using a good headphone or a great Hi-Fi audio-system. I hope the pictures give a nice impression of the coldness of that desolate city evening. It's on the spot I made this recording. Short track search: ' klankbeeld 130220_02 ' Recorded: evening, February 2013 7-8 pm, Herautstraat, 's-Hertogenbosch Weather: wind 2-3 bft NE, clear sky, temp 0c, Rode NT4 in blimp > Sony PCM D50 Tip of the day: When you record in a peaceful city, level your recorder on -35 / -30 dB for the low level general-noise (quiet moments). Than the close slamming doors and car-horns will not kill your hard freezing work. Do not record on a lower level, cause you miss to much of the ambiance details (the quiet sounds). If you have one, switch the limiter on if you have one. You'll never know..... name: AmbienceCity-Trafego-Vancouver-Hastings-MuitoMovimento-Obra-no Ponto de onibus.mp3
description:
Sounds recorded at a bus stop near a busy corner between two avenues in Vancouver where I lived for some years. Recorded in March 1996. Besides the sounds of cars and traffic, has many details of horns, buses getting to the point, some people passing by, the cars horns a much , because a group of workers are repainring the pavement and part of Hastings was closed to made room for them . ultimately a very rich set of street sounds.
------------------
Sons gravados em um ponto de onibus proximo a uma esquina emtre duas avenidas movimentadas em Vancouver aonde moreipor alguns anos. Gravado em am março de 1996. Além dos sons de carros e do trafego normal , tem muitos detalhes de buzinas, onibus chegando no ponto, algumas pessoas que passam perto, os carros buzinam muito, pois haviam homem trabalhando em reparo no piso da avenida e parte da rua estava cercada para dar espaço a els. Enfim, é um conjunto muito rico de sons de rua.

name: city from pasture March Bossche Broek LONG 130302_01.flac
description: The down-town begins 300 m from here. I'm standing in the pasture early March. As far as I know, there is no down-town so close to the fields (see geaotag)in Europe, but I could be wrong. The traffic just behind the old city-wall. People let there dog's (and kids ;-) out here. Cause it's cold and cloudy between winter and spring there are not many birds around. The carillon (bells) of the st. Jan's cathedral and the far city-hall give this recording the image of a city in the distance. Sometimes the trains (left) are audible. Even the audio signal of the traffic-light 300m away is there. And the two planes are for free. I know this is a long recording, but I like to listen to the details. Hope you like it too. Short recording here Time table (everything far): general; far people traffic and a few birds 00.00 13.08 22.57 28.02 29.32 bells and/or carillon 02.07 12.15 16.50 18.05 plane high altitude 02.53 05.55 11.43 18.00 22.17 30.35 car horn(s) 07.56 15.20 traffic-light ticker 14.04 small dog barking 14.47 20.10 train history of the waters around the city In the Middle Ages' the city of s-Hertogenbosch was an almost impregnable fortress. The city was built on a low sandy hill in the wetlands, which was wet with the rivers 'Dommel' and 'Dieze'. In 1579 the Spaniards still managed to take the city.'s-Hertogenbosch became a Catholic stronghold. Frederick Hendrik in 1629 called in the help of the famous water-engeneer Leeghwater. Thanks to his dike system the land could be insinuated (flooded) and so the people of 's-Hertogenbosch got back the city into their own hands. Through the work of Leeghwater the area I'm standing named 'Bossche Broek' became a controllable wetland, a marshy parkland area along the lower reaches of the river Dommel. These days the area still can be flooded when the surrounding rivers (Maas, Aa, Dieze and Dommel)are to high. Recorded: March 2 2013 2.30-3 pm, Singelgrachtweg, Bossche Broek, 's-Hertogenbosch. Holland (Netherlands). Weather: wind 0-2 bft between W – NEN, temp 3c, cloudy. Gear: Rode NT4 (batt. Power) in Rode Blimp > Sony PCM D50. Edit: Audacity freeware. name: wind indoors 002 150823_0735.wav
description: Wind outside, recorded inside. Recorded in an apartment building. The outer doors are open. I'm standing in the hallway with the indoor doors closed. Before and behind the building trees in the wind and rain. The rustling of the leaves is clearly audible as monotonous hiss. The sunscreen slats tapping the radiator. As the sound in the building comes from below and from above. Left and right of the microphones, the wind howls through gaps under the doors. Sometimes traffic is audible. At the end a car horn. Gear chain: Rode NT4 XY and Rode NTG1, in Rode Blimp > Sound Devices 302 >Tascam dr-100 Mk2. name: passenger train sounds - track, rail squeal, click clack, horn, crossing bells
description:
Here are some train sounds I recorded while riding a tourist railroad which had two floor passenger cars (Santa Fe Hi-Liners). I placed the microphone in the area where you cross between cars (which is on the upper level). Note that the sound of people can often be heard so sorry about that. The right microphone was closer to the sound source.

27:37 passing by RR crossing bells (and also once more before this time)
47:00 some good rail squeal around this time

recorded with a Sony ICD UX560

Leave a comment. I would love to see what you do with my sounds!
